# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: academician
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:academician/academia-europaea] The **Academia Europaea** is a pan-European academy of humanities, letters, law, and sciences.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] The Academia was founded in 1988 as a functioning Europe-wide Academy that encompasses all fields of scholarly inquiry.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] It acts as co-ordinator of European interests in national research agencies.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] The concept of a 'European Academy of Sciences' was raised at a meeting in Paris of the European Ministers of Science in 1985.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] The meeting also included Brian Flowers and John Kendrew.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] In October 1986 a larger meeting with participants representing some countries in the Council of Europe supported the development of a European academy.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] The name *Academia Europaea* was decided on in a meeting in December 1987 as a "linguistically neutral" name.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] The foundation meeting was held in Cambridge in September 1988 and Arnold Burgen became the first president of the academy.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] Hubert Curien, who was at that time the French Minister of Science (and later became the second President of the Academia), gave the inaugural address and provided the active support of the French government.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] The first Plenary Meeting was held in London in June 1989, by which time there were 627 members.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] The Royal Society supported Academia Europaea financially as it worked to secure broader funding.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] Since 1989, the Academia Europaea has evolved from its origins as an organization of predominantly "western European" scholars into a pan-European Academy of Sciences, Humanities and Letters.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] The funding of the Academy is based on an original endowment, contributions from some of the member countries, special projects and by other organizations like the Leopoldina, which is also supporting the Academia Europaea financially.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] When the European Academies' Science Advisory Council was founded, Academia Europaea became a member.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] It does not aim to replace existing national academies.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] The objectives were kept deliberately broad, covering the humanities, social and natural sciences, so as to ensure interdisciplinary discourse and activities.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] Initial activities were to include annual meetings of members, multidisciplinary meetings, an interdisciplinary journal, a newsletter, providing independent advice, improving mobility of scholars within Europe and improving public understanding of science.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] Academia Europaea covers a range of subjects, including law, humanities, social sciences, physical sciences, religion and history.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] Impact has been achieved through workshop meetings and reports, for instance to committees under the Council of Europe, on topics such as education, psychosocial problems among the youth, and the development of research academies in specific parts of Europe.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] The scholarly interests of the Academia are managed through a section structure.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] On election, all members are assigned to a section.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] The Academia elects members from 47 Council of Europe states in recognition of their academic achievements.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] Election to the membership has been celebrated by several institutions as an honour each year.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] Elected members are entitled to the post-nominal letters **MAE**.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] SAPEA pulls together scientific expertise from the pan-European Academia and more than 100 European national academies from over 40 countries, collectively providing independent policy advice to the European Commissioners.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] The Academia serves as official advisor to the European Union under the Scientific Advice Mechanism.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] The Academia Europaea has published *European Review* (*ER*) since 1993 on behalf of members and in conjunction with Cambridge University Press (since 1998).
[src:academician/academia-europaea] It is a quarterly, peer-reviewed, international journal.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] Editorial control is in the hands of an independent board.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] *European Review* publishes articles and reviews that will be of broad interest to an intellectual readership, world-wide.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] Contributions come from academics, professionals and those in public life and address multidisciplinary and interdisciplinary issues across the sciences arts, humanities and letters.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] *European Review* provides the AE with a vehicle for publication of articles from sponsored conferences and workshops.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] The editorial board invites contributions and reviews from opinion leaders world-wide.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] *European Review* has become available fully on-line.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] The registered office and headquarters of the Academia Europaea is in London.
[src:academician/academia-europaea] This is also the location of the General Secretariat.
[src:academician/academic-staff] In British and Australian/New Zealand English, "faculty" usually refers to a sub-division of a university (usually the teaching/research staff of one or a group of departments).
[src:academician/academic-staff] In contrast, in North America "faculty" refers to the people who teach and research, and is distinguished from "staff", who are hired in administrative, operations, and support roles.
[src:academician/academic-staff] For example the *Faculty Handbook* at Boston University defines faculty as Assistant, Associate, and Full Professors, those with professorial titles modified by “Research,” “Clinical,” and “of the Practice, Lecturers of all ranks, and Instructors.
[src:academician/academic-staff] In the United States and parts of Canada, universities, community colleges and even some secondary and primary schools use the term *faculty*.
[src:academician/academic-staff] Other institutions (e.g., teaching hospitals or not-for-profit research institutes) may likewise use the term *faculty*.
[src:academician/academic-staff] In parts of the US, the term *academic staff* can be synonymous with just *staff*, which instead refers to staff that is not primarily involved with teaching or research.
[src:academician/academic-staff] The higher education regulatory body of India, University Grants Commission, defines academic staff as teachers, librarians, and physical education personnel.
[src:academician/academic-staff] In countries like the Philippines, faculty is used more broadly to refer to teaching staff of either a basic or higher education institution.
[src:academician/academic-staff] In many universities, the members of the administration (e.g., department chairs, deans, vice presidents, presidents, and librarians) are also faculty members; many of them begin (and remain) as professors.
[src:academician/academic-staff] These two types of faculty members are sometimes known as "nine-month faculty" and "twelve-month faculty".
[src:academician/academic-staff] Faculty who are paid a nine-month salary are typically allowed to seek external funds from grant agencies to partially or fully support their research activities during the summer months.
[src:academician/academic-staff] Librarians are a special case in that they are educators like faculty who belong to degree granting departments, not necessarily administrators who have management responsibilities like Deans, Presidents, and Vice Presidents.
[src:academician/academic-staff] Most university faculty members hold a Ph.D. or equivalent highest-level degree in their field.
[src:academician/academic-staff] Some professionals or instructors from other institutions who are associated with a particular university (e.g., by teaching some courses or supervising graduate students) but do not hold professorships may be appointed as adjunct faculty.
[src:academician/academic-staff] In North America, faculty is a distinct category from staff, although members of both groups are employees of the institution in question.
[src:academician/academic-staff] This is distinct from, for example, the British (and European, Australia, and New Zealand) usage, in which all employees of the institution are staff either on academic or professional (i.e. non-academic) contracts.
[src:academician/academician] An **academician** is a full member of an artistic, literary, engineering, or scientific academy.
[src:academician/academician] In many countries, it is an honorific title used to denote a full member of an academy that has a strong influence on national scientific life.
[src:academician/academician] Accordingly, within systems such as the Academy of Sciences of the USSR, the title grants privileges and administrative responsibilities for funding allocation and research priorities.
[src:academician/academician] Being an academician in China is a top honour and title granted only to the nation's top scientists and engineers.
[src:academician/academician] Academicians are elected through either the Chinese Academy of Sciences and Chinese Academy of Engineering.
[src:academician/academician] The British honours "Fellow of the Royal Society" (FRS) or Fellow of the Academy of Social Sciences can be considered rough equivalents.
[src:academician/academician] Fellowship of the Academy of Social Sciences was known as the Award of Academician until July 2014.
[src:academician/academician] Fellows of the Royal Academy of Engineering in the UK are recognized as academicians and members include Nobel Prize winners and the nation's top engineers and scientists.
[src:academician/academician] Recently, Nobel Prize winner Frances Arnold was elected to the Royal Academy of Engineering.
[src:academician/academician] In the United States of America, academicians are elected members of the National Academy of Sciences and National Academy of Engineering.
[src:academician/academician] Members include many Nobel Prize, Turing Awards, and Fields Medalists.
[src:academician/academician] Sweden does not use the Academician concept, but membership in learned societies are noted in the Swedish State Calendar.
[src:academician/academician] The Swedish Royal Academies are independent organizations, founded on Royal command, that act to promote the arts, culture, and science in Sweden.
[src:academician/academician] The Swedish Academy and Academy of Sciences who are responsible for the selection of Nobel Prize laureates in Literature, Physics, Chemistry, and the Prize in Economic Sciences.
[src:academician/academician] Also included in the Royal Academies are scientific societies that were granted Royal Charters.
[src:academician/academician] There are a few esteemed Swedish learned societies that has not sought Royal command, including the Society of Sciences in Lund.
[src:academician/academician] Academician may also be a functional title and denote a full member of the National Academy of Sciences in those countries where the academy has a strong influence on national scientific life, particularly countries that were part of, or influenced by, the Soviet Union.
[src:academician/academician] In such countries, academician is used as an honorific title (like "Doctor", "Professor", etc.) when addressing or speaking about someone.
[src:academician/academician] However, since the reforms of late USSR dismantled the de facto monopoly of the state on forming academies, the creation of voluntary academies has been allowed.
[src:academician/academician] Therefore, it became customary and almost compulsory to list which academy gave the title to assert its meaningfulness.
[src:academician/academician] In Europe, academicians are elected by Pan-European academies, such as the European Academy of Sciences and Arts and the Academia Europaea.
[src:academician/academician] In Canada, fellowship of the Royal Society of Canada is a comparable honour.
[src:academician/academician] In Finland, "Academician" (Finnish: *akateemikko*, Swedish: *akademiker*) is an honorary title and the President of the Republic nominates the Academicians.
[src:academician/academician] There can be 12 Finnish Academicians representing science and scholarly pursuits and eight Academicians representing fine arts and literature at the same time.
[src:academician/academician] The Academy of Finland is the state funding agency of Finnish science and letters, but it has no organizational connection to Finnish Academicians.
[src:academician/academician] The scientists and scholars funded by the Academy of Finland are called Academy Professors (Finnish: *akatemiaprofessori*, Swedish: *akademiprofessor*) and Academy Research Fellows (Finnish: *akatemiatutkija*, Swedish: *akademiforskare*).
[src:academician/academician] In addition to Academy of Finland, Finland has four independent national academies.
[src:academician/academician] Finnish academies are less recognized globally due to its lack of international exposure and use of English language.
[src:academician/academician] In Taiwan, elected members of *Academia Sinica* are considered academicians.
[src:academician/academician] A related option of membership also exists in some countries—a *Corresponding Member* is a person who is eminent in respect of scientific results but cannot or does not wish to become a full academy member.
[src:academician/academician] One of the reasons for this may be that they live far from the academy and it is inconvenient to often travel to its headquarters.
[src:academician/academician] It is, for example, the case when the person is not a resident in the country which the academy belongs to.
[src:academician/academician] For communication, such a scientist uses "correspondence".
[src:academician/academician] Another possible reason is that the charter or traditions of the academy do not admit election of a person to a full membership, unless they have been a corresponding member for a certain period and has demonstrated additional achievements within this period.
[src:academician/academician] Because of this, in the Russian Academy of Sciences a corresponding membership is a seen as a lower level of membership as compared to the academicians.
[src:academician/academy-of-finland] The **Research Council of Finland** (Finnish: *Suomen Akatemia*, Swedish: *Finlands Akademi*) is a governmental funding body for scientific research in Finland.
[src:academician/academy-of-finland] Until August 2023, its official English-language name was **Academy of Finland**.
[src:academician/academy-of-finland] Yearly, the council administers over 260 million euros to Finnish research activities.
[src:academician/academy-of-finland] Over 5000 researchers are working on projects supported by the council.
[src:academician/academy-of-finland] The Academy of Finland should not be confused with The Finnish Academy of Science and Letters (*Suomalainen tiedeakatemia*) and the Finnish Society of Science and Letters (*Finska Vetenskaps-Societeten*) which are the two Finnish learned societies for scientists and scholars.
[src:academician/academy-of-finland] For engineers, there are two language-based honorary academies, the Finnish Academy of Technology (*Teknillisten Tieteiden Akatemia*) and the Swedish Academy of Engineering Sciences in Finland (*Svenska tekniska veteskapsakademien i Finland*).
[src:academician/academy-of-finland] The Finnish title of Academician (*akateemikko / akademiker*) is an award given by the President of Finland upon the recommendation of the Research Council to the most distinguished Finnish scientists, scholars and artists.
[src:academician/academy-of-finland] It may also be bestowed on foreign scientists, scholars or artists who have contributed very significantly to Finnish intellectual life.
[src:academician/academy-of-finland] At any time, there may be a maximum of 12 living scientific and scholarly academicians and eight living artistic academicians.
[src:academician/academy-of-finland] The number of foreign academicians is not limited.
[src:academician/academy-of-finland] The Academicians do not have any organizational connection to the Academy of Finland, although this was the requisite for membership in 1947–1969.
[src:academician/academy-of-finland] Personnel funded by the Research Council can use the title referring to it, e.g. distinguished professors funded by the council are called Academy Professors.
[src:academician/academy-of-finland] The funding period for Academy professors is 5 years.
[src:academician/academy-of-finland] The Academy of Finland appoints Academy Professors.
[src:academician/academy-of-finland] There are 32 serving currently, with two carrying specific name and branch.
[src:academician/academy-of-finland] *Minna Canth Academy Professor* focuses on Social equality and Women's studies.
[src:academician/academy-of-finland] *Martti Ahtisaari Academy Professor* focuses on International Conflict management.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] The **Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union** was the highest scientific institution of the Soviet Union from 1925 to 1991.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] It united the country's leading scientists and was subordinated directly to the Council of Ministers of the Soviet Union (until 1946 the Council of People's Commissars of the Soviet Union).
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] In 1991, by the decree of the President of the Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic, the Russian Academy of Sciences was established on the basis of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] In the first years of Soviet Russia, the Institute of the Academy of Sciences was perceived rather ambiguously as a closed and elite scientific education.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] However, in 1918, after negotiations with the then leadership of the Academy of Sciences, which had already been renamed from "Imperial" to "Russian", cooperation began with the new government.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] The financing of the academy was entrusted to the People's Commissariat for Education and the Central Commission for the Improvement of the Life of Scientists.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] In 1925, its 200th anniversary was solemnly celebrated.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] A new charter was adopted for this date.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] The first president of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union was the well-known scientist, geologist Alexander Karpinsky, who previously held the presidency of the Russian Academy of Sciences.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] Attempts to establish state and party control over the previously independent Academy began in the mid-1920s: in 1925 the academy was subordinated to the Council of People's Commissars of the Soviet Union.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] In 1928, under pressure from the authorities, a number of new Communist members were elected to it.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] In January 1929, the academicians defiantly failed the three Communist candidates, Vladimir Fritsche, Nikolai Lukin and Abram Deborin, who were running for the Academy of Sciences, but already in February, under conditions of extreme pressure, they were forced to reconsider their decision.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] In 1929, a government commission headed by Yuri Petrovich Figatner was sent to Leningrad to "cleanse" the academy.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] In June–December 1929, by its decision, 128 full-time employees (out of 960) and 520 supernumerals (out of 830) were dismissed from the Academy of Sciences.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] Sergey Oldenburg was removed from the post of the permanent secretary of the academy at the end of October 1929, defending her independence.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] After that, the party-state bodies established full control over the academy.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] A new Presidium of the Academy of Sciences was elected.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] Even before this, on February 25, 1929, the Politburo issued a special decision: to leave Alexander Karpinsky as president, Gleb Krzhizhanovsky, Nikolai Marr, and Vladimir Komarov as vice-presidents, and Vyacheslav Volgin as the permanent secretary.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] Thus, for the first time in the practice of the Academy of Sciences, its leading core was directively appointed at a meeting of the highest party body with subsequent automatic approval at the General Assembly, and this also became a precedent for subsequent practice.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] During the period from December 1929 to December 1930, over 100 people were arrested under the "Academic Case" (mainly experts in the humanities, primarily historians).
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] In February – April 1930, a new charter of the Academy of Sciences was developed and approved.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] The development of the project was entrusted to an academic commission approved by the plenary session of the Committee for the Management of Scientists and Educational Institutions of the Central Executive Committee of the Soviet Union, headed by Vyacheslav Volgin.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] The first meeting of the commission to draw up a charter and reorganize the Academy of Sciences was held on February 28, 1930.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] The draft of the new charter was discussed and approved by the session of the Academy of Sciences on March 31 – April 5, 1930, and it approved the first work plan of the Academy of Sciences for 1931–1932.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] On April 4, 1930, the charter was adopted at the General Assembly.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] In 1930, in connection with the reorganization of the Soviet government, the Academy of Sciences was transferred to the Central Executive Committee of the Soviet Union.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] In 1934, the Presidium of the academy and 14 scientific institutes were transferred from Leningrad (formerly and now St.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] Petersburg) to Moscow (On April 25, 1934, Vyacheslav Molotov signed the corresponding decree of the Council of People's Commissars of the Soviet Union).
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] As Felix Perchenok noted, "the transfer of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union to Moscow – one of the most important steps towards turning it into the headquarters of Soviet science – was carried out in a fire order".
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] In 1935, the permanent secretary of the academy, Vyacheslav Volgin, wrote a letter to Joseph Stalin asking for his release from the position of permanent secretary.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] In the letter, he stressed that he alone was doing the difficult work of an indispensable secretary all the time, while other members of the party group only "threw out ideas", sometimes useful, sometimes fantastic.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] For five years in this post, Volgin not only could not continue his scientific work, but could not even read books in his specialty, could not follow the development of his science.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] "Meanwhile", he adds, "I was considered in the well-known narrow field as the best expert on the subject".
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] "I'm already 56 years old", Vyacheslav Petrovich continues, "and there is not much time left for science.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] A few more years – and I will not be able to return to science".
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] Moreover, in a letter to Stalin, he noted that in the party group, he no longer feels the former positive assessment of his work.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] On August 8, 1935, at a meeting of the Politburo, it was proposed to release Vyacheslav Volgin from the post of permanent secretary of the academy.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] On November 20, 1935, by resolution of the general meeting of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union, he was thanked for his work in the governing bodies of the Academy of Sciences and freed from the duties of an indispensable secretary.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] His place was taken by the former affairs manager of the Council of People's Commissars Nikolai Gorbunov.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] By the decree of the Presidium of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union dated June 26, 1937, this position was abolished altogether, and since that time administrative officers have performed the duties of secretaries.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] From 1945 to 1970, the total number of researchers (including faculty and research personnel of higher education) increased more than sevenfold: from 130 thousand to 950 thousand people.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] One of the notable figures of this time was the economist Lev Gatovsky, which became director of the Institute of Economics of the academy from 1965 to 1971.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] In 1980 and 1985, the total number of research workers was already 1.4 and 1.5 million, respectively.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] The total number of scientific, scientific, pedagogical, design and design organizations of various types from 1945 to 1985 also increased steadily and amounted in the Soviet Union as a whole to 1,700, 5,300, and 5,100 successively in 1945, 1970 and 1985.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] For its achievements, the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union was twice awarded the Order of Lenin: in 1969 and 1974.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] In 1932, the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union organized its first branches – the Ural and the Far East – and research bases – the Kazakh and Tajik.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] In 1933, the Transcaucasian branch was established with branches in Armenia and Azerbaijan, and in 1934, the Kola Research Base.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] In 1935, Azerbaijan, and in 1936 the Armenian branch of the Transcaucasian branch were transformed into independent branches of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] In 1936, the Northern Base appeared, in 1939 the Uzbek Base, and in 1941, on the eve of the Great Patriotic War, the Turkmen branch.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] By the end of 1941, the Academy of Sciences had 7 branches (Azerbaijan, Armenian, Kazakh, Tajik, Turkmen, Uzbek, and Ural), two research bases (Kola and North), and one mountain taiga station.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] The scientific institutions of the branches and bases of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union at that time had about 1,500 scientific and technical workers, including 12 academicians, 11 corresponding members, 126 doctors, 284 candidates of science, 610 scientists without a scientific degree.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] In connection with the collapse of the Soviet Union, the scientific institutions of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union, located in the former Soviet republics and which were part of the academies of sciences of the Union republics, became part of the new independent states.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] In fact, the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union was the Russian Academy of Sciences.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] In December 1991, elections to the Russian Academy of Sciences were held, and the scientists who took part in these elections, together with the full members of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union, constituted the Russian Academy of Sciences.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] In 1992, the International Association of Academies of Sciences was established.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] The objectives of the activities of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union were to promote the full implementation of scientific advances in the practice of communist construction in the USSR; identification and development of the most important and fundamental areas of science.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] Coordination was also conducted through regional offices and republican academies of sciences.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] The research activity of the academy was conducted in a network of institutes, laboratories, observatories.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] The network of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union included 295 scientific institutions.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] The Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union had its own publishing house, a research fleet, a network of libraries.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] The Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union awarded awards to scientists who have made significant contributions to the development of science.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] On 1 January 1936 the Academy of Sciences had 98 active members.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] The organs of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union were formed exclusively on an electoral basis.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] The supreme body is the General Meeting of Academicians and Corresponding Members.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] To guide the academy in the periods between sessions of the General Assembly, it elects every 4 years the Presidium of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussr] Critics noted that, despite the broadest powers and formal responsibility for the state and development of all science in the Soviet Union, during its existence, the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union did not come up with any serious project reforming Soviet science.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences] An **academy of sciences** is a type of learned society or academy (as special scientific institution) dedicated to sciences that may or may not be state funded.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences] Some state funded academies are national, or royal (i.e.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences] United Kingdom's Royal Society of London for Improving Natural Knowledge) as a form of honor.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences] The other type of academies are *Academy of Arts* or combination of both (e.g., American Academy of Arts and Sciences).
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences] *Academy of Letters* is another related expression, encompassing literature.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences] In non-English-speaking countries, the range of academic fields of the members of a national Academy of Science often includes scholarly disciplines which would not normally be classed as "science" in English.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences] Many languages use a broad term for systematized learning which includes both natural sciences and social sciences and fields such as literary studies, linguistics, history, or art history.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences] As the engineering sciences have become more varied and advanced, there is a recent trend in many advanced countries to organize the National Academy of Engineering (or National Academy of Engineering Sciences), separate from the national academy of sciences.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences] Academies of science play an important role in science diplomacy efforts.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences] Academies are increasingly organized in regional or even international academies.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences] The Interacademy Partnership for example is a global network consisting of over 140 national, regional and global member academies of science, engineering and medicine.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences] Pan-Europe academies include the Academia Europaea and the European Academy of Sciences and Arts.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences] Additionally, there are many regional associations such as ALLEA in Europe, NASAC as the Network of African Science Academies, IANAS in Latin America, and AASSA in Asia.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences] The International Science Council brings together international scientific unions and associations as well as national and regional scientific organizations such as academies and research councils from the natural sciences, social sciences and the humanities.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences] Apart from national academies of science, there are now increasingly also national young academies.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences] National young academies usually select members for a limited term, normally 4–5 years, after which members become academy alumni.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences] Young academies typically engage with issues important to young scientists.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences] These include, for example, science education or the dialog between science and society.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences] Most young academies are affiliated with a senior Academy of Sciences or with a network of senior academies.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences] The Global Young Academy, which itself is a science academy (e.g. full member of Interacademy Partnership) often serves as a facilitator of the growing global network of young academies.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences] Since its creation, more than 35 national young academies have been established.
[src:academician/academy-of-sciences] In 2019, there were 41 national young academies.
[src:academician/academy-of-social-sciences] The **Academy of Social Sciences** (**AcSS**) is a representative body for social sciences in the United Kingdom.
[src:academician/academy-of-social-sciences] The academy promotes social science through its sponsorship of the Campaign for Social Science, its links with Government on a variety of matters, and its own policy work in issuing public comment, responding to official consultations, and organising meetings and events about social science.
[src:academician/academy-of-social-sciences] It confers the title of Fellow upon nominated social scientists following a process of peer review.
[src:academician/academy-of-social-sciences] The academy comprises over 1000 fellows and 41 learned societies based in the UK and Europe.
[src:academician/academy-of-social-sciences] The academy's origins lie in the formation of a representative body for the social science learned societies in 1982, the **Association of Learned Societies in the Social Sciences** (**ALSISS**).
[src:academician/academy-of-social-sciences] From 1999 to 2007 it was called the Academy of Learned Societies for the Social Sciences before changing to its current name.
[src:academician/academy-of-social-sciences] The academy is run by a council of 21 members, with Professor Roger Goodman FAcSS as its current chair, and Professor Sir Ivor Crewe FAcSS, Master of University College, Oxford, as its current president.
[src:academician/academy-of-social-sciences] Seven council members are elected by the academy's fellows, 7 by its learned societies and seven are appointed.
[src:academician/academy-of-social-sciences] Since 2019, its chief executive has been Rita Gardner FAcSS.
[src:academician/academy-of-social-sciences] The academy advocates social science by interacting with Government and other organisations, and co-ordinates the responses of social scientists to Government consultation documents.
[src:academician/academy-of-social-sciences] The academy also puts forward suggestions to the Government about which social scientists should carry out its Foresight research projects, which look at important issues and how these might change over the next 20 to 80 years.
[src:academician/academy-of-social-sciences] A developing part of the academy's work is to bring researchers and organisations using research closer together to improve the evidence upon which public policy is based and to increase the impact of research.
[src:academician/academy-of-social-sciences] The academy has produced a series of "Making the Case for the Social Sciences" booklets which give examples of important social science research which has made a difference to policy or practice.
[src:academician/academy-of-social-sciences] These are: Wellbeing; Ageing; Sustainability; the Environment and Climate Change; Crime; Sport and Leisure; Management; Scotland; Longitudinal Studies, Mental Wellbeing, Wales and Dementia.
[src:academician/academy-of-social-sciences] The academy also publishes a cross-disciplinary peer-reviewed journal, *Contemporary Social Science*.
[src:academician/academy-of-social-sciences] The academy holds regular events, such as conferences on the ethics of social media research and the future of the Research Excellence Framework.
[src:academician/academy-of-social-sciences] It holds an annual lecture each summer, and its President's Lunch each winter.
[src:academician/academy-of-social-sciences] It also arranges (with the British Library) a public lecture series Enduring Ideas.
[src:academician/academy-of-social-sciences] Part of the academy's work is to recognise social scientists who are held in esteem by their peer group and whose life and work have had an impact in advancing social science.
[src:academician/academy-of-social-sciences] They are nominated and the nominations are then subject to peer review.
[src:academician/academy-of-social-sciences] Fellows are academics, policy-makers and practitioners, and are entitled to use the letters "FAcSS" after their name.
[src:academician/academy-of-social-sciences] In November 2014 there were 1000 Fellows, just over 1% of the 90,000 total membership of the 41 learned society members of the academy.
[src:academician/academy-of-social-sciences] Fellows were previously known as academicians and used the post-nominal letter "AcSS".
[src:academician/academy-of-social-sciences] This was changed in July 2014 to bring the academy in line with other British learned societies.
[src:academician/academy-of-social-sciences] The Academy launched the Campaign for Social Science in January 2011 to advocate social science to Government and the general public.
[src:academician/academy-of-social-sciences] It has campaigned for the restoration of the post of Government Chief Social Scientific Adviser, promotes social science in the media and on the web, and organises roadshows around the country to emphasise the value and importance of social science.
[src:academician/academy] An **academy** (Attic Greek: Ἀκαδήμεια; Koine Greek: Ἀκαδημία) is an institution of tertiary education.
[src:academician/academy] The name traces back to Plato's school of philosophy, founded c.
[src:academician/academy] 386 BC at Akademia, a sanctuary of Athena, the goddess of wisdom and skill, north of Athens, Greece.
[src:academician/academy] The Royal Spanish Academy defines an academy as a scientific, literary or artistic society established with public authority and as a teaching establishment, public or private, of a professional, artistic, technical or simply practical nature.
[src:academician/academy] The word comes from the *Academy* in ancient Greece, which derives from the Athenian hero, *Akademos*.
[src:academician/academy] Outside the city walls of Athens, the gymnasium was made famous by Plato as a center of learning.
[src:academician/academy] The sacred space, dedicated to the goddess of wisdom, Athena, had formerly been an olive grove, hence the expression "the groves of Academe".
[src:academician/academy] In these gardens, the philosopher Plato conversed with followers.
[src:academician/academy] Plato developed his sessions into a method of teaching philosophy and in 387 BC, established what is known today as the Old Academy.
[src:academician/academy] By extension, *academia* has come to mean the accumulation, development and transmission of knowledge across generations as well as its practitioners and transmitters.
[src:academician/academy] In the 17th century, British, Italian and French scholars used the term to describe types of institutions of higher learning.
[src:academician/academy] Before *Akademia* was a school, and even before Cimon enclosed its precincts with a wall, it contained a sacred grove of olive trees dedicated to Athena, the goddess of wisdom, outside the city walls of ancient Athens.
[src:academician/academy] The archaic name for the site was *Hekademia*, which by classical times evolved into *Akademia* and was explained, at least as early as the beginning of the 6th century BC, by linking it to an Athenian hero, a legendary "Akademos".
[src:academician/academy] The site of *Akademia* was sacred to Athena and other immortals.
[src:academician/academy] Plato's immediate successors as "scholarch" of *Akademia* were Speusippus (347–339 BC), Xenocrates (339–314 BC), Polemon (314–269 BC), Crates (c.
[src:academician/academy] Later scholarchs include Lacydes of Cyrene, Carneades, Clitomachus, and Philo of Larissa ("the last undisputed head of the Academy").
[src:academician/academy] Other notable members of *Akademia* include Aristotle, Heraclides Ponticus, Eudoxus of Cnidus, Philip of Opus, Crantor, and Antiochus of Ascalon.
[src:academician/academy] After a lapse during the early Roman occupation, *Akademia* was refounded as a new institution of some outstanding Platonists of late antiquity who called themselves "successors" (*diadochoi*, but of Plato) and presented themselves as an uninterrupted tradition reaching back to Plato.
[src:academician/academy] However, there cannot have actually been any geographical, institutional, economic or personal continuity with the original Academy in the new organizational entity.
[src:academician/academy] The emperor Justinian ceased the school's funding in AD 529, a date that is often cited as the end of Antiquity.
[src:academician/academy] According to the sole witness, the historian Agathias, its remaining members looked for protection under the rule of Sassanid king Khosrau I in his capital at Ctesiphon, carrying with them precious scrolls of literature and philosophy, and to a lesser degree of science.
[src:academician/academy] After a peace treaty between the Persian and the Byzantine empire in 532 guaranteed their personal security (an early document in the history of freedom of religion), some members found sanctuary in the pagan stronghold of Harran, near Edessa.
[src:academician/academy] One of the last leading figures of this group was Simplicius, a pupil of Damascius, the last head of the Athenian school.
[src:academician/academy] It has been speculated that *Akademia* did not altogether disappear.
[src:academician/academy] After his exile, Simplicius (and perhaps some others), may have travelled to Harran, near Edessa.
[src:academician/academy] From there, the students of an academy-in-exile could have survived into the 9th century, long enough to facilitate the Arabic revival of the Neoplatonist commentary tradition in Baghdad.
[src:academician/academy] In ancient Greece, after the establishment of the original Academy, Plato's colleagues and pupils developed spin-offs of his method.
[src:academician/academy] Arcesilaus, a Greek student of Plato established the Middle Academy.
[src:academician/academy] Carneades, another student, established the New Academy.
[src:academician/academy] In 335 BC, Aristotle refined the method with his own theories and established the Lyceum in another gymnasium.
[src:academician/academy] The Musaeum, Serapeum and library of Alexandria Egypt was frequented by intellectuals from Africa, Europe and Asia studying various aspects of philosophy, language and mathematics.
[src:academician/academy] The University of Timbuktu was a medieval university in Timbuktu, present-day Mali, which comprised three schools: the Mosque of Djinguereber, the Mosque of Sidi Yahya, and the Mosque of Sankore.
[src:academician/academy] During its zenith, the university had an average attendance of around 25,000 students within a city of around 100,000 people.
[src:academician/academy] In China a higher education institution Shang Xiang was founded by Shun in the Youyu era before the 21st century BC.
[src:academician/academy] The Imperial Central Academy at Nanjing, founded in 258, was a result of the evolution of Shang Xiang and it became the first comprehensive institution combining education and research and was divided into five faculties in 470, which later became Nanjing University.
[src:academician/academy] In the 8th century another kind of institution of learning emerged, named Shuyuan, which were generally privately owned.
[src:academician/academy] There were thousands of Shuyuan recorded in ancient times.
[src:academician/academy] The degrees from them varied from one to another and those advanced Shuyuan such as Bailudong Shuyuan and Yuelu Shuyuan (later become Hunan University) can be classified as higher institutions of learning.
[src:academician/academy] Taxila or Takshashila, in ancient India, modern-day Pakistan, was an early centre of learning, near present-day Islamabad in the city of Taxila.
[src:academician/academy] It is considered one of the ancient universities of the world.
[src:academician/academy] According to scattered references which were only fixed a millennium later it may have dated back to at least the 5th century BC.
[src:academician/academy] Some scholars date Takshashila's existence back to the 6th century BC.
[src:academician/academy] The school consisted of several monasteries without large dormitories or lecture halls where the religious instruction was most likely still provided on an individualistic basis.
[src:academician/academy] Takshashila is described in some detail in later Jātaka tales, written in Sri Lanka around the 5th century AD.
[src:academician/academy] It became a noted centre of learning at least several centuries BC, and continued to attract students until the destruction of the city in the 5th century AD.
[src:academician/academy] Takshashila is perhaps best known because of its association with Chanakya.
[src:academician/academy] The famous treatise Arthashastra (Sanskrit for The knowledge of Economics) by Chanakya, is said to have been composed in Takshashila itself.
[src:academician/academy] Chanakya (or Kautilya), the Maurya Emperor Chandragupta and the Ayurvedic healer Charaka studied at Taxila.
[src:academician/academy] Generally, a student entered Takshashila at the age of sixteen.
[src:academician/academy] The Vedas and the Eighteen Arts, which included skills such as archery, hunting, and elephant lore, were taught, in addition to its law school, medical school, and school of military science.
[src:academician/academy] Nalanda was established in the 5th century AD in Bihar, India.
[src:academician/academy] It was founded in 427 in northeastern India, not far from what is today the southern border of Nepal.
[src:academician/academy] It survived until 1197 when it was set upon, destroyed and burnt by the marauding forces of Ikhtiyar Uddin Muhammad bin Bakhtiyar Khilji.
[src:academician/academy] It was devoted to Buddhist studies, but it also trained students in fine arts, medicine, mathematics, astronomy, politics and the art of war.
[src:academician/academy] The center had eight separate compounds, 10 temples, meditation halls, classrooms, lakes and parks.
[src:academician/academy] It had a nine-story library where monks meticulously copied books and documents so that individual scholars could have their own collections.
[src:academician/academy] It had dormitories for students, perhaps a first for an educational institution, housing 10,000 students in the university's heyday and providing accommodation for 2,000 professors.
[src:academician/academy] Nalanda University attracted pupils and scholars from Korea, Japan, China, Tibet, Indonesia, Persia and Turkey.
[src:academician/academy] The geographical position of Persia allowed it to absorb cultural influences and ideas from both west and east.
[src:academician/academy] This include the spread of the Greek form of schools in the new Hellenistic cities built in Persia after the invasion of Alexander the Great.
[src:academician/academy] Under the Sasanians, Syriac became an important language of the administration and intellectuals, rivaling Greek.
[src:academician/academy] Several cities developed centers of higher learning in the Sasanian Empire, including Mosul, al-Hira, and Harran (famous for the Pythagorean School of the Sabians).
[src:academician/academy] The Grand School was the main center of learning in the Persian capital Ctesiphon, but little is known about it.
[src:academician/academy] Perhaps the most famous center of learning in Persia was the Academy of Gundishapur, teaching medicine, mathematics, astronomy, and logic.
[src:academician/academy] The academy was later instrumental in founding the Muslim city of Baghdad as a center of learning, and serving as the model for the first Muslim hospital (*bimaristan*) at Damascus.
[src:academician/academy] Founded in Fes, University of Al-Karaouine in the 9th century and in Cairo, Al-Azhar University in the 10th century, and in Mali, the University of Timbuktu in about 1100.
[src:academician/academy] Mustansiriya Madrasah in Baghdad, Iraq, was established in 1227 as a madrasah by the Abbasid Caliph al-Mustansir.
[src:academician/academy] Its library had an initial collection of 80,000 volumes, given by the Caliph.
[src:academician/academy] The collection was said to have grown to 400,000 volumes.
[src:academician/academy] In Europe, the academy dates to the ancient Greeks and Romans in the pre-Christian era.
[src:academician/academy] Newer universities were founded in the 12th and 13th centuries, and the European institution of academia took shape.
[src:academician/academy] Monks and priests moved out of monasteries to cathedral cities and other towns where they opened the first schools dedicated to advanced study.
[src:academician/academy] The most notable of these new schools were in Bologna and Salerno, Naples, Salamanca, Paris, Oxford and Cambridge, while others were opened throughout Europe.
[src:academician/academy] The seven liberal arts—the Trivium (Grammar, Rhetoric, and Logic), and the Quadrivium (Arithmetic, Geometry, Music, and Astronomy)—had been codified in late antiquity.
[src:academician/academy] This was the basis of the curriculum in Europe until newly available Arabic texts and the works of Aristotle became more available in Europe in the 12th century.
[src:academician/academy] It remained in place even after the new scholasticism of the School of Chartres and the encyclopedic work of Thomas Aquinas, until the humanism of the 15th and 16th centuries opened new studies of arts and sciences.
[src:academician/academy] With the Neoplatonist revival that accompanied the revival of humanist studies, *academia* took on newly vivid connotations.
[src:academician/academy] During the Florentine Renaissance, Cosimo de' Medici took a personal interest in the new Platonic Academy that he determined to re-establish in 1439, centered on the marvellous promise shown by the young Marsilio Ficino.
[src:academician/academy] Cosimo had been inspired by the arrival at the otherwise ineffective Council of Florence of Gemistos Plethon, who seemed a dazzling figure to the Florentine intellectuals.
[src:academician/academy] In 1462 Cosimo gave Ficino a villa at Careggi for the academy's use, situated where Cosimo could see it from his own villa, and drop by for visits.
[src:academician/academy] The academy remained a wholly informal group, but one which had a great influence on Renaissance Neo-Platonism.
[src:academician/academy] In Rome, after unity was restored following the Western Schism, humanist circles, cultivating philosophy and searching out and sharing ancient texts tended to gather where there was access to a library.
[src:academician/academy] The Vatican Library was not coordinated until 1475 and was never catalogued or widely accessible: not all popes looked with satisfaction at gatherings of unsupervised intellectuals.
[src:academician/academy] At the head of this movement for renewal in Rome was Cardinal Bessarion, whose house from the mid-century was the centre of a flourishing academy of Neoplatonic philosophy and a varied intellectual culture.
[src:academician/academy] His valuable Greek as well as Latin library (eventually bequeathed to the city of Venice after he withdrew from Rome) was at the disposal of the academicians.
[src:academician/academy] Bessarion, in the latter years of his life, retired from Rome to Ravenna, but he left behind him ardent adherents of the classic philosophy.
[src:academician/academy] He was a worshipper not merely of the literary and artistic form, but also of the ideas and spirit of classic paganism, which made him appear a condemner of Christianity and an enemy of the Church.
[src:academician/academy] In his academy every member assumed a classical name.
[src:academician/academy] The prisoners begged so earnestly for mercy, and with such protestations of repentance, that they were pardoned.
[src:academician/academy] The Letonian academy, however, collapsed.
[src:academician/academy] In Naples, the *Quattrocento* academy founded by Alfonso of Aragon and guided by Antonio Beccadelli was the *Porticus Antoniana*, later known as the *Accademia Pontaniana*, after Giovanni Pontano.
[src:academician/academy] The 16th century saw at Rome a great increase of literary and aesthetic academies, more or less inspired by the Renaissance, all of which assumed, as was the fashion, odd and fantastic names.
[src:academician/academy] We learn from various sources the names of many such institutes; as a rule, they soon perished and left no trace.
[src:academician/academy] In the 1520s came the *Accademia degli Intronati*, for the encouragement of theatrical representations.
[src:academician/academy] There were also the academy of the "Vignaiuoli", or "Vinegrowers" (1530), and the *Accademia della Virtù* (1542), founded by Claudio Tolomei under the patronage of Cardinal Ippolito de' Medici.
[src:academician/academy] These were followed by a new academy in the "Orti" or Farnese gardens.
[src:academician/academy] There were also the academies of the "Intrepidi" (1560), the "Animosi" (1576), and the "Illuminati" (1598); this last, founded by the Marchesa Isabella Aldobrandini Pallavicino.
[src:academician/academy] Towards the middle of the 16th century there were also the academy of the "Notti Vaticane", or "Vatican Nights", founded by St.
[src:academician/academy] Charles Borromeo; an "Accademia di Diritto civile e canonico", and another of the university scholars and students of philosophy (Accademia Eustachiana).
[src:academician/academy] As a rule these academies, all very much alike, were merely circles of friends or clients gathered around a learned man or wealthy patron, and were dedicated to literary pastimes rather than methodical study.
[src:academician/academy] They fitted in, nevertheless, with the general situation and were in their own way one element of the historical development.
[src:academician/academy] Despite their empirical and fugitive character, they helped to keep up the general esteem for literary and other studies.
[src:academician/academy] Cardinals, prelates, and the clergy in general were most favourable to this movement, and assisted it by patronage and collaboration.
[src:academician/academy] The private Accademia degli Incamminati set up later in the century in Bologna by the Carracci brothers was also extremely influential, and with the Accademia di San Luca of Rome (founded 1593) helped to confirm the use of the term for these institutions.
[src:academician/academy] Gradually academies began to specialize on particular topics (arts, language, sciences) and began to be founded and funded by the kings and other sovereigns (few republics had an academy).
[src:academician/academy] And, mainly, since 17th century academies spread throughout Europe.
[src:academician/academy] In the 17th century the tradition of literary-philosophical academies, as circles of friends gathering around learned patrons, was continued in Italy; the "Umoristi" (1611), the "Fantastici (1625), and the "Ordinati", founded by Cardinal Dati and Giulio Strozzi.
[src:academician/academy] About 1700 were founded the academies of the "Infecondi", the "Occulti", the "Deboli", the "Aborigini", the "Immobili", the "Accademia Esquilina", and others.
[src:academician/academy] During the 18th century many Italian cities established similar philosophical and scientific academies.
[src:academician/academy] The Académie de peinture et de sculpture in Paris, established by the monarchy in 1648 (later renamed) was the most significant of the artistic academies, running the famous Salon exhibitions from 1725.
[src:academician/academy] A fundamental feature of academic discipline in the artistic academies was regular practice in making accurate drawings from antiquities, or from casts of antiquities, on the one hand, and on the other, in deriving inspiration from the other fount, the human form.
[src:academician/academy] Students assembled in sessions drawing the draped and undraped human form, and such drawings, which survive in the tens of thousands from the 17th through the 19th century, are termed ***académies*** in French.
[src:academician/academy] Similar institutions were often established for other arts: Rome had the Accademia di Santa Cecilia for music from 1585; Paris had the Académie Royale de Musique from 1669 and the Académie Royale d'Architecture from 1671.
[src:academician/academy] In 1582 five Florentine literati gathered and founded the Accademia della Crusca to demonstrate and conserve the beauty of the Florentine vernacular tongue, modelled upon the authors of the Trecento.
[src:academician/academy] The main instrument to do so was the *Vocabolario degli Accademici della Crusca*.
[src:academician/academy] The Crusca long remained a private institution, criticizing and opposing the official Accademia Fiorentina.
[src:academician/academy] The first institution inspired by the Crusca was the Fruitbearing Society for German language, which existed from 1617 to 1680.
[src:academician/academy] The Crusca inspired Richelieu to found in 1634 the analogous Académie française with the task of acting as an official authority on the French language, charged with publishing the official dictionary of that language.
[src:academician/academy] The following year the Académie received letters patent from King Louis XIII as the only recognized academy for French language.
[src:academician/academy] In its turn the state established Académie was the model for the *Real Academia Española* (founded in 1713) and the Swedish Academy (1786), which are the ruling bodies of their respective languages and editors of major dictionaries.
[src:academician/academy] It also was the model for the Russian Academy, founded in 1783, which afterwards merged into the Russian Academy of Sciences.
[src:academician/academy] After the short-lived Academia Secretorum Naturae of Naples, the first academy exclusively devoted to sciences was the Accademia dei Lincei founded in 1603 in Rome, particularly focused on natural sciences.
[src:academician/academy] In 1657 some students of Galileo founded the Accademia del Cimento (Academy of Experiment) in Florence, focused on physics and astronomy.
[src:academician/academy] The foundation of academy was funded by Prince Leopoldo and Grand Duke Ferdinando II de' Medici.
[src:academician/academy] In 1652 was founded the Academia Naturae Curiosorum by four physicians.
[src:academician/academy] In 1677, Leopold I, Holy Roman Emperor, recognised the society and in 1687 he gave it the epithet *Leopoldina*, with which is internationally famous., p.
[src:academician/academy] 7–8; So, it became the academy of sciences for the whole Holy Roman Empire.
[src:academician/academy] In 1662 Charles II of England signed a Royal Charter which created the "Royal Society of London", then "Royal Society of London for the Improvement of Natural Knowledge".
[src:academician/academy] In 1666 Colbert gathered a small group of scholars to found a scientific society in Paris.
[src:academician/academy] The first 30 years of the academy's existence were relatively informal, since no statutes had as yet been laid down for the institution.
[src:academician/academy] In contrast to Royal Society, the academy was founded as an organ of government.
[src:academician/academy] In 1699, Louis XIV gave the academy its first rules and named it Académie royale des sciences.
[src:academician/academy] Although Prussia was a member of Holy Roman Empire, in 1700 Prince-elector Frederick III of Brandenburg founded its own Prussian Academy of Sciences upon the advice of Gottfried Leibniz, who was appointed president.
[src:academician/academy] This kind of academy lost importance after the university reform begun with the foundation of the University of Berlin, when universities were provided with laboratories and clinics, and were charged with doing experimental research.
[src:academician/academy] Academic societies or learned societies began as groups of academics who worked together or presented their work to each other.
[src:academician/academy] These informal groups later became organized and in many cases state-approved.
[src:academician/academy] Membership was restricted, usually requiring approval of the current members and often total membership was limited to a specific number.
[src:academician/academy] The Royal Society founded in 1660 was the first such academy.
[src:academician/academy] In 1720, King John V of Portugal approved the founding and gave royal patronage to the Royal Academy of Portuguese History which had been meeting informally, since 1717, under the sponsorship of the 4th Count of Ericeira.
[src:academician/academy] The American Academy of Arts and Sciences was begun in 1780 by many of the same people prominent in the American Revolution.
[src:academician/academy] Academic societies served both as a forum to present and publish academic work, the role now served by academic publishing, and as a means to sponsor research and support academics, a role they still serve.
[src:academician/academy] Membership in academic societies is still a matter of prestige in modern academia.
[src:academician/academy] Starting at the end of the 16th century in the Holy Roman Empire, France, Poland and Denmark, many Knight academies were established to prepare the aristocratic youth for state and military service.
[src:academician/academy] Many of them lately turned into gymnasiums, but some of them were transformed into true military academies.
[src:academician/academy] The Royal Danish Military Academy began to educate all officers for the Royal Danish Army by request of King Frederick IV in 1713.
[src:academician/academy] The École Militaire was founded by Louis XV in 1750 with the aim of creating an academic college for cadet officers from poor families.
[src:academician/academy] The construction began in 1752, but the school did not open until 1760.
[src:academician/academy] The Theresian Military Academy was founded on 14 December 1751 by Maria Theresa of Austria.
[src:academician/academy] Per year the academy accepted 100 noblemen and 100 commoners to start their education there.
[src:academician/academy] These were the model for the subsequent military academies throughout Europe, like the *Reale Accademia Militare* of Naples in 1787 and the Military Academy Karlberg in 1792.
[src:academician/academy] The term is used widely today to refer to anything from schools to learned societies to funding agencies to private industry associations.
[src:academician/academy] National academies are bodies for scientists, artists or writers that are usually state-funded and often are given the role of controlling much of the state funding for research into their areas, or other forms of funding.
[src:academician/academy] Some use different terms in their name – the British Royal Society for example.
[src:academician/academy] The membership typically comprises distinguished individuals in the relevant field, who may be elected by the other members, or appointed by the government.
[src:academician/academy] They are essentially not schools or colleges, though some may operate teaching arms.
[src:academician/academy] The Académie Française was the most influential pattern for these.
[src:academician/academy] Finland even has two separate "academies": Academy of Finland is a government-run funding agency, Suomalainen tiedeakatemia is a learned society.
[src:academician/academy] The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences, which presents the annual Academy Awards, is an example of a purely industry body using the name.
[src:academician/academy] College-type specialized academies include the Royal Academy of Music of the United Kingdom; the United States Military Academy at West Point, New York; the United States Naval Academy; United States Air Force Academy; and the Australian Defence Force Academy.
[src:academician/academy] In emulation of the military academies, police in the United States are trained in police academies.
[src:academician/academy] Because of the tradition of intellectual brilliance associated with this institution, many groups have chosen to use the word "academy" in their name, especially specialized tertiary educational institutions.
[src:academician/academy] In the early 19th century "academy" took the connotations that "gymnasium" was acquiring in German-speaking lands, of school that was less advanced than a college (for which it might prepare students) but considerably more than elementary.
[src:academician/academy] Early American examples are the prestigious preparatory schools of Phillips Andover Academy, Phillips Exeter Academy and Deerfield Academy.
[src:academician/academy] In England, "academy" had a specialized meaning for schools, but the Edinburgh Academy was more like the American examples.
[src:academician/academy] Academy was also used very loosely for various commercial training schools for dancing and the like.
[src:academician/academy] Mozart organized public subscription performances of his music in Vienna in the 1780s and 1790s, he called the concerts "academies".
[src:academician/academy] This usage in musical terms survives in the concert orchestra Academy of St Martin in the Fields and in the Brixton Academy, a concert hall in Brixton, South London.
[src:academician/academy] Academies proliferated in the 20th century until even a three-week series of lectures and discussions would be termed an "academy".
[src:academician/academy] In addition, the generic term "the academy" is sometimes used to refer to all of academia, which is sometimes considered a global successor to the academy of Athens.
[src:academician/academy] In France, regional academic councils called academies are responsible for supervising all aspects of education in their region.
[src:academician/academy] The academy regions are similar to, but not identical to, the standard French administrative regions.
[src:academician/academy] The rector of each academy is a revocable nominee of the Ministry of Education.
[src:academician/academy] These academies' main responsibility is overseeing primary and secondary education, but public universities are in some respects also answerable to the academy for their region.
[src:academician/academy] However, French private universities are independent of the state and therefore independent of the regional academies.
[src:academician/academy] In Imperial Russia and Soviet Union the term "academy", or Academy of Sciences was reserved to denote a state research establishment, see Russian Academy of Sciences.
[src:academician/academy] The latter one still exists in Russia, although other types of academies (study and honorary) appeared as well.
[src:academician/academy] From the mid-seventeenth to the 19th centuries, educational institutions in England run by nonconformist groups that did not agree with the Church of England teachings were collectively known as "the dissenting academies".
[src:academician/academy] As a place at an English public school or university generally required conformity to the Church of England, these institutions provided an alternative for those with different religious views and formed a significant part of England's educational system.
[src:academician/academy] In 2000, a form of "independent state schools", called "academies", were introduced in England.
[src:academician/academy] They have been compared to US charter schools.
[src:academician/academy] They are directly funded from central government rather than through local councils, and are partly privately sponsored.
[src:academician/academy] Often the sponsors are from business, but some are sponsored by universities and charities.
[src:academician/academy] These schools have greater autonomy than schools run by the local councils.
[src:academician/academy] They are usually a type of secondary school, but some are "all through" schools with an integral primary school.
[src:academician/academy] Some of the early ones were briefly known as "city academies"—the first such school opening on 10 September 2002 at the Business Academy Bexley.
[src:academician/academy] The Queen's Speech, which followed the 2010 general election, included proposals for a bill to allow the Secretary of State for Education to approve schools, both Primary and Secondary, that have been graded "outstanding" by Ofsted, to become academies.
[src:academician/academy] This was to be through a simplified streamlined process not requiring sponsors to provide capital funding.
[src:academician/academy] In 2012, the UK government began forcing some schools which had been graded satisfactory or lower into becoming academies, unilaterally removing existing governing bodies and head teachers in some cases.
[src:academician/academy] An example was Downhills Primary School in Haringey, where the head teacher refused to turn the school into an academy.
[src:academician/academy] OFSTED were called in to assess the school, failed it, and both the head and the governing body were removed and replaced with a Government-appointed board despite opposition from the school and parents.
[src:academician/academy] Prior to the twentieth century, education was not as carefully structured in the United States as it is in the twenty-first.
[src:academician/academy] There was not a rigid division between high school and colleges.
[src:academician/academy] The typical college at first included a preparatory unit, which it dropped by 1900.
[src:academician/academy] In the 1800s an academy was what later became known as a high school; in most places in the US there were no public schools above the primary level.
[src:academician/academy] Some older high schools, such as Corning Free Academy, retained the term in their names (Corning Free Academy, later becoming a middle school, closed in 2014).
[src:academician/academy] In 1753, Benjamin Franklin established the academy and Charitable School of the Province of Pennsylvania.
[src:academician/academy] In 1755, it was renamed the college and Academy and Charitable School of Philadelphia.
[src:academician/academy] Today, it is known as the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:academician/academy] The United States Military Academy was formed in 1802 as a college.
[src:academician/academy] The academy movement in the US in the early 19th century arose from a public sense that education in the classic disciplines needed to be extended into the new territories and states that were being formed in the new western states.
[src:academician/academy] Thousands of academies were started using local funds and tuition; most closed after a few years and others were established.
[src:academician/academy] In 1860 there were 6,415 academies in operation.
[src:academician/academy] When the Civil War erupted in 1861 they generally closed down temporarily; most in the South never reopened.
[src:academician/academy] During the Age of Enlightenment in 18th-century Europe, the academy started to change in Europe.
[src:academician/academy] In the beginning of the 19th century Wilhelm von Humboldt not only published his philosophical paper *On the Limits of State Action*, but also directed the educational system in Prussia for a short time.
[src:academician/academy] He introduced an academic system that was much more accessible to the lower classes.
[src:academician/academy] Humboldt's Ideal was an education based on individuality, creativity, wholeness, and versatility.
[src:academician/academy] Many continental European universities are still rooted in these ideas (or at least pay lip-service to them).
[src:academician/academy] They are, however, in contradiction to today's massive trend of specialization in academia.
[src:academician/academy] An **academic** is a person who works as a teacher or researcher at a university or other higher education institution.
[src:academician/academy] An academic usually holds an advanced degree.
[src:academician/academy] The term *scholar* is sometimes used with equivalent meaning to that of *academic* and describes in general those who attain mastery in a research discipline.
[src:academician/academy] It has wider application, with it also being used to describe those whose occupation was research prior to organized higher education.
[src:academician/academy] Academic administrators such as university presidents are not typically included in this use of the term *academic*, although many administrators hold advanced degrees and pursue scholarly research and writing while also tending to their administrative duties.
[src:academician/academy] In the United States, the term academic is approximately synonymous with that of the job title professor although in recent decades a growing number of institutions include librarians in the category of "academic staff".
[src:academician/academy] In the United Kingdom, various titles of academic rank are used, typically research associate, research fellow (also senior research fellow and principal research fellow), lecturer (also senior lecturer and principal lecturer), reader, and professor.
[src:academician/academy] The colloquial term don is sometimes substituted for teaching staff at Oxford and Cambridge.
[src:academician/academy] Academia is usually conceived as divided into *disciplines* or *fields* of study.
[src:academician/academy] These have their roots in the subjects of the medieval trivium and quadrivium, which provided the model for scholastic thought in the first universities in medieval Europe.
[src:academician/academy] The disciplines have been much revised, and many new disciplines have become more specialized, researching smaller and smaller areas.
[src:academician/academy] Because of this, *interdisciplinary* research is often prized in today's academy, though it can also be made difficult both by practical matters of administration and funding and by differing research methods of different disciplines.
[src:academician/academy] In fact, many new fields of study have initially been conceived as interdisciplinary, and later become specialized disciplines in their own right – a recent example is cognitive science.
[src:academician/academy] Most academic institutions reflect the divide of the disciplines in their administrative structure, being divided internally into *departments* or *programs* in various fields of study.
[src:academician/academy] Each department is typically administered and funded separately by the academic institution, though there may be some overlap and faculty members, research and administrative staff may in some cases be shared among departments.
[src:academician/academy] In addition, academic institutions generally have an overall administrative structure (usually including a president and several deans) which is controlled by no single department, discipline, or field of thought.
[src:academician/academy] Also, the tenure system, a major component of academic employment and research in the US, serves to ensure that academia is relatively protected from political and financial pressures on thought.
[src:academician/academy] The degree awarded for completed study is the primary academic qualification.
[src:academician/academy] Typically these are, in order of completion, associate's degree, bachelor's degree (awarded for completion of undergraduate study), master's degree, and doctorate (awarded after graduate or postgraduate study).
[src:academician/academy] These are only currently being standardized in Europe as part of the Bologna process, as many different degrees and standards of time to reach each are currently awarded in different countries in Europe.
[src:academician/academy] In most fields the majority of academic researchers and teachers have doctorates or other terminal degrees, though in some professional and creative fields it is common for scholars and teachers to have only master's degrees.
[src:academician/academy] Closely related to academic publishing is the practice of bringing a number of intellectuals in a field to give talks on their research at an academic conference, often allowing for a wider audience to be exposed to their ideas.
[src:academician/academy] Nepotism is frequent in academia where it is frequent for professors to have their partners, and sometimes children, hired by the same faculty in which they work.
[src:academician/academy] Universities are often culturally distinct from the towns or cities where they reside.
[src:academician/academy] In some cases this leads to discomfort or outright conflict between local residents and members of the university over political, economic, or other issues.
[src:academician/academy] Some localities in the Northeastern United States, for instance, have tried to block students from registering to vote as local residents—instead encouraging them to vote by absentee ballot at their primary residence—in order to retain control of local politics.
[src:academician/academy] Other issues can include deep cultural and class divisions between local residents and university students.
[src:academician/academy] The film *Breaking Away* dramatizes such a conflict.
[src:academician/academy] Among the earliest research journals were the Proceedings of Meetings of the Royal Society in the 17th century.
[src:academician/academy] At that time, the act of publishing academic inquiry was controversial, and widely ridiculed.
[src:academician/academy] It was not at all unusual for a new discovery to be announced as an anagram, reserving priority for the discoverer, but indecipherable for anyone not in on the secret: both Isaac Newton and Leibniz used this approach.
[src:academician/academy] Merton, a sociologist, found that 92 percent of cases of simultaneous discovery in the 17th century ended in dispute.
[src:academician/academy] The number of disputes dropped to 72 percent in the 18th century, 59 percent by the latter half of the 19th century, and 33 percent by the first half of the 20th century.
[src:academician/academy] The decline in contested claims for priority in research discoveries can be credited to the increasing acceptance of the publication of papers in modern academic journals.
[src:academician/academy] The Royal Society was steadfast in its unpopular belief that science could only move forward through a transparent and open exchange of ideas backed by experimental evidence.
[src:academician/academy] Many of the experiments were ones that we would not recognize as scientific today—nor were the questions they answered.
[src:academician/academy] For example, when the Duke of Buckingham was admitted as a Fellow of the Royal Society on June 5, 1661, he presented the Society with a vial of powdered "unicorn horn".
[src:academician/academy] It was a well-accepted 'fact' that a circle of unicorn's horn would act as an invisible cage for any spider.
[src:academician/academy] Robert Hooke, the chief experimenter of the Royal Society, emptied the Duke's vial into a circle on a table and dropped a spider in the centre of the circle.
[src:academician/academy] The spider promptly walked out of the circle and off the table.
[src:academician/academy] In its day, this was cutting-edge research.
[src:academician/academy] Research journals have been so successful that the number of journals and of papers has proliferated over the past few decades, and the credo of the modern academic has become "publish or perish".
[src:academician/academy] Except for generalist journals such as *Science* or *Nature*, the topics covered in any single journal have tended to be narrow, and readership and citation have declined.
[src:academician/academy] A variety of methods for reviewing submissions exist.
[src:academician/academy] The most common involves initial approval by the journal, peer review by two or three researchers working in similar or closely related subjects who recommend approval or rejection as well as request error correction, clarification or additions before publishing.
[src:academician/academy] Controversial topics may receive additional levels of review.
[src:academician/academy] Journals have developed a hierarchy, partly based on reputation but also on the strictness of the review policy.
[src:academician/academy] More prestigious journals are more likely to receive and publish more important work.
[src:academician/academy] Submitters try to submit their work to the most prestigious journal likely to publish it to bolster their reputation and curriculum vitae.
[src:academician/academy] Andrew Odlyzko, an academician with a large number of published research papers, has argued that research journals will evolve into something akin to Internet forums over the coming decade, by extending the interactivity of current Internet preprints.
[src:academician/academy] This change may open them up to a wider range of ideas, some more developed than others.
[src:academician/academy] Whether this will be a positive evolution remains to be seen.
[src:academician/academy] Some claim that forums, like markets, tend to thrive or fail based on their ability to attract talent.
[src:academician/academy] Some believe that highly restrictive and tightly monitored forums may be the least likely to thrive.
[src:academician/academy] Gowns have been associated with academia since the birth of the university in the 14th and 15th centuries, perhaps because most early scholars were priests or church officials.
[src:academician/academy] Over time, the gowns worn by degree-holders have become standardized to some extent, although traditions in individual countries and even institutions have established a diverse range of gown styles, and some have ended the custom entirely, even for graduation ceremonies.
[src:academician/academy] At some universities, such as the Universities of Oxford and Cambridge, undergraduates may be required to wear gowns on formal occasions and on graduation.
[src:academician/academy] Undergraduate gowns are usually a shortened version of a bachelor's gown.
[src:academician/academy] At other universities, for example, outside the UK or US, the custom is entirely absent.
[src:academician/academy] Students at the University of Trinity College at the University of Toronto wear gowns to formal dinner, debates, to student government, and to many other places.
[src:academician/academy] In general, in the US and UK, recipients of a bachelor's degree are entitled to wear a simple full-length robe without adornment and a mortarboard cap with a tassel.
[src:academician/academy] In addition, holders of a bachelor's degree may be entitled to wear a ceremonial hood at some schools.
[src:academician/academy] In the US, bachelor's hoods are rarely seen.
[src:academician/academy] Bachelor's hoods are generally smaller versions of those worn by recipients of master's and doctoral degrees.
[src:academician/academy] Recipients of a master's degree in the US or UK wear a similar cap and gown but closed sleeves with slits, and usually receive a ceremonial hood that hangs down the back of the gown.
[src:academician/academy] In the US the hood is traditionally edged with a silk or velvet strip displaying the disciplinary color, and is lined with the university's colors.
[src:academician/academy] Recipients of a doctoral degree tend to have the most elaborate academic dress, and hence there is the greatest diversity at this level.
[src:academician/academy] In the US, doctoral gowns are similar to the gowns worn by master's graduates, with the addition of velvet stripes across the sleeves and running down the front of the gown which may be tinted with the disciplinary color for the degree received.
[src:academician/academy] Holders of a doctoral degree may be entitled or obliged to wear *scarlet* (a special gown in scarlet) on high days and special occasions.
[src:academician/academy] While some doctoral graduates wear the mortarboard cap traditional to the lower degree levels, most wear a cap or *Tudor bonnet* that resembles a tam o'shanter, from which a colored tassel is suspended.
[src:academician/academy] In modern times, in the US and UK, gowns are normally only worn at graduation ceremonies, although some colleges still demand the wearing of academic dress on formal occasions (official banquets and other similar affairs).
[src:academician/academy] In the 19th and early 20th centuries, it was more common to see the dress worn in the classroom, a practice which has now all but disappeared.
[src:academician/academy] Two notable exceptions are Oxford and a society at Sewanee, where students are required to wear formal academic dress in the examination room.
